Headline::::
Why are more children being prescribed antidepressants? Funding cuts




DateTime::::2016-03-11T13:45:57+0000



<p><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.europeanneuropsychopharmacology.com/article/S0924-977X(16)00037-7/abstract" title="">New research</a> published <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-35763210" title="">this week shows</a> that between 2005 and 2013 there was a 54% increase in the number of children and young people prescribed antidepressants in the UK. The World Health Organisation’s director of mental health, Dr Shekhar Saxena, has <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/number-of-children-prescribed-anti-depressants-increases-by-50-in-seven-years-a6920576.html" title="">expressed concern</a> about the reasons behind this rise.</p>

<p>Antidepressants are not licensed for prescription <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.rcpsych.ac.uk/healthadvice/treatmentswellbeing/antidepressants.aspx" title="">for under-18s</a>, with one exception. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence clinical guidelines state that fluoxetine, a type of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitor, can be used in under-18s, but should not be prescribed without first referring the child for <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/may/28/talking-therapies-better-than-pills-report-depression" title="">talking therapy</a>. The two treatments should coexist and the child should be monitored carefully, particularly in the first few weeks after starting the drug, when the risk of the “major harm” Saxena speaks of is at its highest.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/education/2014/jul/29/chilld-and-adolescent-mental-health-service-failing-children">Children are suffering as mental health services fail to cope, say parents and teachers</a> </p>

<p>When starting an antidepressant, there can be an initial period – usually a couple of weeks, sometimes a bit longer – of side-effects. Some people have none at all. Others find that, along with physical symptoms such as tiredness, their anxiety or depressive rumination increases before things get better. And they do get better for many people.</p>

<p>A rise in prescriptions for antidepressants in under-18s throws up all kinds of fears. The idea that, after a five-minute consultation in a primary care setting (<a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35756602" title="">as has been reported</a>), a child might be prescribed a psychotropic drug is very troubling. Although the medication may work well, such initial treatment doesn’t just speak of oversubscribed surgeries or poor GP training – it signifies just how weak the bridge between the distressed young person and the specialist care they need and deserve has become. But GPs are often left with no other option. If the wait times for young patients to get psychological therapy referrals are so long, what are they meant to do in the meantime to support a child and their family?</p>

<p>One London-based GP I spoke to, who wished to remain anonymous, said: “Every time I see a teenager whose mental health is suffering and send them – and usually a parent – out the door with nothing but a promise of a referral for therapy that I know is going to take months, I carry the anger home with me. I’m incredibly reluctant to prescribe an antidepressant for someone under the age of 18, as more severe issues should not be managed in primary care, but with the obstacles in place and when presented with extreme distress, it can sometimes feel like the only option to help in the interim. We can’t not do anything.”</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/feb/26/mental-illness-misery-childhood-traumas">Mental illness is a result of misery, yet still we stigmatise it | Richard Bentall</a> </p>

<p>Since 2010 the budget for child and adolescent mental health services (Camhs) has fallen in England by nearly <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-30735370" title="">£50m</a>. A leaked report by a government taskforce <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/feb/13/mental-health-services-crisis-britain-revealed-leaked-report" title="">last month</a> painted a devastating picture of our mental health services, including figures that show the average waiting time for a child to see a specialist was 21 weeks. Twenty-one weeks – that’s nearly half a year.</p>

<p>When researching my <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Anxiety-Beginners-A-Personal-Investigation-y/dp/1509813233" title="">book on anxiety</a>, I spoke to the mother of a teenage boy with obsessive compulsive disorder who had been self-harming. Between the initial GP referral to their local Camhs, which was going to take upwards of eight weeks, her son cut himself so badly she had to take him to A&amp;E. It was only then, with such an acute presentation of distress, that he was scooped up by the system and helped to recalibrate.</p>

<p>I mention this because this boy’s mother talked a lot about the moralising of antidepressants when I met her. The GP had told her they might become an option at some point, but she told me how she’d struggled with the idea of them and how many preconceived notions she had of what taking an antidepressant meant. “Happy pills” was a phrase she used a lot. A mild dose of antidepressant medication did become part of her son’s treatment plan and her perspective has shifted significantly now she sees how much better he’s doing at school and at home, with regular supervision from his care team and GP.</p>

<p class="pullquote-paragraph">Evidence tells us that the sooner mental health problems are dealt with, the better</p>

<p>We cannot say that antidepressants aren’t a reasonable option for some children who become unwell. Suspending judgment and allowing for nuanced argument is so important. No child should feel like they’re strange or are in sure danger if they are to take this type of medication, if it’s deemed appropriate with thorough conversation and therapeutic support. Their self-stigma is likely to already be high. No parent or caregiver should feel guilty, either, or like they have failed in any way. It cannot be as black and white as that. Sticking to binaries when it comes to mental health isn’t helpful for anyone.</p>

<p>Every brain, and therefore every person, is individual. <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/feb/01/stephen-fry-to-feature-in-bbc1-mental-health-season" title="">Stephen Fry</a>, who talks about his mental health in very biomedical terms – as a chemical imbalance in his brain, only treatable with medication – was politely but <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://blogs.canterbury.ac.uk/discursive/all-in-the-brain/" title="">rigorously challenged in an open letter</a> by <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/profile/richard-bentall" title="">Richard Bentall</a>, a professor of clinical psychology, who explained that discussing mental distress solely in terms of chemicals makes it easy to believe that human beings can be divided into two subspecies: mentally well or mentally ill. In fact, the borders are fuzzy and highly subjective. Bentall did not criticise or damn medication, he only asked Fry – and all of us, by extension – to have a more open, nuanced attitude to the hows and whys surrounding mental health.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/dec/09/mental-health-antidepressants-ssri-anxiety-medication">Antidepressants get a bad rap – but they saved my life | Anonymous</a> </p>

<p>Mental illness is multicausal. This is true for adults as well as children. Myriad factors are at play, including genetics, but also the infinite variables of life experience. Scientific research can offer no precise reason why one person experiences disordered <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/15/anxiety-epidemic-gripping-britain" title="">anxiety</a> over another, for example. With acute mental distress, particularly with conditions such as anxiety, someone’s symptoms need to be addressed in the first instance – as they are often profoundly physical and uncomfortable – before examining what might be the causal factors and to start addressing thinking patterns. Medication can be part of those first steps.</p>

<p>Evidence tells us that the sooner mental health problems are dealt with, the better. Adolescents are still developing cognitively and early intervention bodes far better for the future. Antidepressants are not a panacea for adults or children, but it’s crucial with studies like this that we try to consider the whole picture, rather than just honing in on the drugs themselves. In the UK, what we’re looking at is the product of our mental healthcare system being suffocated by government-funding cuts. Empty promises of big cash injections have a human reality: distressed children, in need of specialist treatment, having to wait, and needing something.</p>




