Author::::Maritz
DateTime::::2016-03-12T01:09:41Z
I'm not sure I agree that manic episodes which develop into psychotic breaks are something that can be overcome with a bit of discipline and an understanding of the condition. The depression experienced by people with Bipolar disorder is also extremely intense and as such dangerous and something sufferers shouldn't be left to deal with thanks to a bit of therapy, yoga and herbal tea. Bipolar is one mental illness that is very well understood to be caused by demonstrably biological triggers and is often responsive to older and less expensive treatments like lithium. A person for whom I care very deeply was diagnosed after her first psychotic episode, which she luckily survived, and successfully treated with that drug. She had only one other episode, within a year or two, while in graduate school. She decided it was worth the risk to stop her medication and ride the wave of the mania she hoped that would trigger in order to get more done in less time. She knew this might happen the last time mania-induced sleeplessness and a hyper mind made her think she had an edge in the earlier stages of the psychosis. Luckily she called me while in the throes of the mania - I called her husband and mum saying she sounded like she was manic again - she went back on her meds, had to push back her school deadlines, but is now a successful professional and mum of 2 and takes her meds faithfully. When I hear or read someone downplaying the role of meds like lithium in changing the lives of those with manic depressive illness I imagine that time I thought that person I cared for so deeply would either die or see all her hopes and dreams, multitudinous due to her extreme intelligence and talent, come to nothing at the tender age of 17. I celebrate that there are treatments available for those with mental illness and that other than a few necessary adjustments they no longer present the probability of ruined relationships, job instability and unstable family lives.



