Author::::angelsoup
DateTime::::2016-03-11T22:34:54Z
On 27 January the BMA published the results of 70 trials of most common anti depressants, which found they doubled risk of suicide and aggressive behaviour in under 18's. This was reported in a Daily Telegraph article by Sarah Knapton on same day. She wrote that comparisons of clinical trials with actual patient reports found that pharmaceutical companies had routinely misclassified deaths and suicides in people taking anti depressants 'to favour products.' NHS guidelines state under 18's should not be given anti depressants. 'I don't remember reading a report of an inquest where a suicide verdict was applied to a child who had never been on psychiatric mediation,' said a father of a son who committed suicide. One thing young people don't need is anti depressants.



